      "  Step 2: The ENTIRE canvas background is one saturated wash in that hue, pushed toward a soft editorial tone (peach-pink for warm products, true red for bold red products, strawberry-pink for pink/red products, denim-blue for blue products, sage-green for green products, honey-amber for amber, etc.). The wash has a subtle gradient — slightly brighter behind the product, slightly deeper toward the corners.",
      "  Step 3: Every prop, every typography color, every UI element pulls from the same tonal family. The accent color for highlighted UI (the spec card border, the color-swatch outline, the [+] bullet glyph) is a deeper saturated version of the wash. White is allowed only for typography contrast where strictly necessary.",
      "  Step 4: Edge case — if the product's dominant color is black, white, or a near-neutral gray, pick a single tasteful rich hue based on the product's category (denim-blue for footwear, soft beige for cosmetics, sage-green for skincare). The product itself still renders with its exact reference color, never tinted to match the wash.",
