      "  Step 3: The wash is DEEP and SATURATED (~50–70% saturation, ~25–40% value) — distinct from the moody-near-black backdrop of the botanical style. The wash has a subtle dramatic gradient: a soft radial highlight directly behind the product creates a natural spotlight, falling off to deeper at the corners and edges.",
      "  Step 4: The ACCENT color (used for the right-side feature pill backgrounds, the dot bullets in the top-left pills, the [+] glyph color, the top-left attribute pill backgrounds) is a SLIGHTLY LIGHTER / PINKER version of the wash hue — a desaturated rose-pink on wine wash, a soft peach on amber wash, a desaturated mint on forest wash. This lighter accent creates UI contrast against the deep wash.",
      "  Step 5: Edge case — if the product's source ingredient maps to a near-neutral color (vanilla = cream, coconut = ivory), pick a tasteful adjacent rich hue based on category (deep caramel for vanilla-cream cosmetics, deep slate for charcoal products). The product itself still renders with its exact reference color, never tinted.",
      "The product's own natural colors come through bit-identically. Whatever color the reference shows IS the product's color.",
